1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,870

2
00:00:06,870 --> 00:00:12,660
So welcome, everyone, to the
MIT Energy Initiatives Fall

3
00:00:12,660 --> 00:00:14,400
Colloquium.

4
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:15,830
My name is Bill Green.

5
00:00:15,830 --> 00:00:18,810
I'm the director of the
MIT Energy Initiative.

6
00:00:18,810 --> 00:00:22,600
And this is our biggest
talk of the fall,

7
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:26,980
and it's part of
our ongoing series,

8
00:00:26,980 --> 00:00:29,460
Advancing the Energy Transition.

9
00:00:29,460 --> 00:00:34,680
Today, we're going to hear from
Joseph DeCarolis from the US

10
00:00:34,680 --> 00:00:36,580
Energy Information
Administration.

11
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:40,473
He's the leader of that
important administration.

12
00:00:40,473 --> 00:00:41,890
Maybe I'll just
talk for a minute,

13
00:00:41,890 --> 00:00:46,440
though, about the MIT
Energy Initiative.

14
00:00:46,440 --> 00:00:51,150
MIT Energy Initiative is the
longest established energy

15
00:00:51,150 --> 00:00:57,000
hub at MIT, and we support
a lot of the energy

16
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:58,090
research on campus.

17
00:00:58,090 --> 00:00:59,790
Also, quite a lot of
the policy research

18
00:00:59,790 --> 00:01:02,850
on campus and economic
research related to energy.

19
00:01:02,850 --> 00:01:06,180
We also run the energy
minor for undergraduates

20
00:01:06,180 --> 00:01:08,620
and a variety of other
educational programs related

21
00:01:08,620 --> 00:01:10,600
to energy.

22
00:01:10,600 --> 00:01:15,050
And with the help
from our sponsors,

23
00:01:15,050 --> 00:01:18,940
we fund quite a lot of
important energy research

24
00:01:18,940 --> 00:01:20,220
throughout the campus.

25
00:01:20,220 --> 00:01:22,750
In addition, we
convene discussions

26
00:01:22,750 --> 00:01:27,010
like this one, where
we bring in speakers

27
00:01:27,010 --> 00:01:33,160
who can address different
aspects of the energy transition

28
00:01:33,160 --> 00:01:36,820
and ultimately help to convene
the conversations that will help

29
00:01:36,820 --> 00:01:40,360
to build consensus for solutions
so we can work together to try

30
00:01:40,360 --> 00:01:42,820
to solve the climate problem.

31
00:01:42,820 --> 00:01:48,710
Today's speaker, Dr.
DeCarolis, was formerly

32
00:01:48,710 --> 00:01:50,825
a professor at North
Carolina State University,

33
00:01:50,825 --> 00:01:52,450
and I guess probably
he'll return there

34
00:01:52,450 --> 00:01:55,240
after he leaves the EIA.

35
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:57,610
He's doing his
public service now

36
00:01:57,610 --> 00:02:02,590
as leading the nation's
foremost agency

37
00:02:02,590 --> 00:02:08,590
for collecting and distributing
high quality data related

38
00:02:08,590 --> 00:02:13,150
to energy and one of the
best data sets in the world.

39
00:02:13,150 --> 00:02:15,910
In his own research,
he also works

40
00:02:15,910 --> 00:02:19,880
a lot on software
and modeling methods,

41
00:02:19,880 --> 00:02:22,360
since a key part of
the energy transition

42
00:02:22,360 --> 00:02:24,250
is trying to figure
out where we're going

43
00:02:24,250 --> 00:02:27,280
and what the options
are for the roads ahead.

44
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:29,390
And as I think he'll
probably talk about today,

45
00:02:29,390 --> 00:02:31,540
that can be a challenging task.

46
00:02:31,540 --> 00:02:35,980
And hence his title, stay humble
and prepare for surprises.

47
00:02:35,980 --> 00:02:38,000
No matter what we
project in the computer,

48
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,930
it's probably not going
to go exactly that way.

49
00:02:40,930 --> 00:02:44,139
So without further
ado, Dr. DeCarolis.

50
00:02:44,139 --> 00:02:46,634
[APPLAUSE]

51
00:02:46,634 --> 00:02:49,630

52
00:02:49,630 --> 00:02:50,240
All right.

53
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:52,700
Well, Bill, thanks very
much for the introduction.

54
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:55,610
And yes, it's quite
an honor to be here.

55
00:02:55,610 --> 00:02:57,430
And yes, I did put
the bottom line up

56
00:02:57,430 --> 00:02:59,740
front right there in the
title, that as we think

57
00:02:59,740 --> 00:03:02,140
about the energy
transition, we do

58
00:03:02,140 --> 00:03:05,016
need to stay humble and
prepare for surprises.

59
00:03:05,016 --> 00:03:09,400
So this talk
combines my insights

60
00:03:09,400 --> 00:03:12,830
as a longtime energy
modeler in academia,

61
00:03:12,830 --> 00:03:15,940
as well as my experience as
an administrator at the Energy

62
00:03:15,940 --> 00:03:17,720
Information Administration.

63
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:20,260
So in this talk, I'm not
going to tell you what I think

64
00:03:20,260 --> 00:03:23,140
or what EIA thinks is going to
happen with regard to the energy

65
00:03:23,140 --> 00:03:24,110
transition.

66
00:03:24,110 --> 00:03:28,360
Instead, I want to focus a level
higher and talk about the models

67
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:31,340
that we rely on to
make these projections.

68
00:03:31,340 --> 00:03:33,520
So I'm going to start
by setting the stage

69
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:35,500
and we're going to look
at some historical data

70
00:03:35,500 --> 00:03:38,270
to understand the current
state of the transition.

71
00:03:38,270 --> 00:03:41,510
And then I want to talk about
the practice of modeling.

72
00:03:41,510 --> 00:03:44,210
And there's three components
to this I want to talk about.

73
00:03:44,210 --> 00:03:48,350
One is just the fact that these
models are not crystal balls,

74
00:03:48,350 --> 00:03:51,200
but they do-- they
can serve a purpose.

75
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:54,500
And I want to talk about what
I think the utility of using

76
00:03:54,500 --> 00:03:55,650
these models are.

77
00:03:55,650 --> 00:03:59,990
Second, using EIA an example,
I want to talk about some

78
00:03:59,990 --> 00:04:02,660
of the developments over
the last couple of decades

79
00:04:02,660 --> 00:04:06,530
that took us by surprise and
how our projections tracked

80
00:04:06,530 --> 00:04:08,460
those developments over time.

81
00:04:08,460 --> 00:04:13,130
And third is I want to outline
some of the efforts we're

82
00:04:13,130 --> 00:04:16,130
undertaking in our
long-term modeling program

83
00:04:16,130 --> 00:04:21,240
to better prepare us for
uncertainty about the future.

84
00:04:21,240 --> 00:04:23,390
And we want to
develop the ability

85
00:04:23,390 --> 00:04:27,980
to analyze a wider range
of future scenarios.

86
00:04:27,980 --> 00:04:29,840
There's a lot of
analyzes out there

87
00:04:29,840 --> 00:04:32,940
that explore different aspects
of the energy transition.

88
00:04:32,940 --> 00:04:34,910
Whether you're a modeler
or not, though, I

89
00:04:34,910 --> 00:04:37,400
hope that this talk gives
you some perspective

90
00:04:37,400 --> 00:04:42,050
on how to interpret
some of those studies.

91
00:04:42,050 --> 00:04:43,950
So before I get
into all of that,

92
00:04:43,950 --> 00:04:46,340
though, I did want to give
just a very brief introduction

93
00:04:46,340 --> 00:04:47,670
to EIA.

94
00:04:47,670 --> 00:04:51,380
We are the statistical
and analytic agency

95
00:04:51,380 --> 00:04:53,580
within the Department of Energy.

96
00:04:53,580 --> 00:04:57,470
So there's 13 principal
statistical agencies

97
00:04:57,470 --> 00:04:59,220
across the federal government.

98
00:04:59,220 --> 00:05:03,830
Again, we're a statistical
agency embedded in DOE.

99
00:05:03,830 --> 00:05:06,920
Our mission is to collect,
analyze, and disseminate

100
00:05:06,920 --> 00:05:11,060
independent and impartial energy
information for our stakeholders

101
00:05:11,060 --> 00:05:14,390
so that they can make
better decisions.

102
00:05:14,390 --> 00:05:17,310
You see the word independence
here a couple times.

103
00:05:17,310 --> 00:05:19,100
That's very important to us.

104
00:05:19,100 --> 00:05:23,250
So when we publish
data or a report,

105
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:26,330
we don't have to seek the
formal approval of anyone

106
00:05:26,330 --> 00:05:28,520
else in the federal government.

107
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,710
And that independence
is very important to us,

108
00:05:30,710 --> 00:05:34,340
because it means that we
can focus on doing our work

109
00:05:34,340 --> 00:05:37,922
and providing the best
information we possibly can.

110
00:05:37,922 --> 00:05:39,380
The other thing I
wanted to mention

111
00:05:39,380 --> 00:05:41,770
is that we're also
policy neutral.

112
00:05:41,770 --> 00:05:45,930
So we're not in the business
of developing policy, advising

113
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:48,310
on policy, but we
do analyze policy.

114
00:05:48,310 --> 00:05:50,940
Policy is part of
the energy system.

115
00:05:50,940 --> 00:05:52,890
And so we do want
to be in a position

116
00:05:52,890 --> 00:05:55,330
to be able to analyze policy.

117
00:05:55,330 --> 00:05:57,870
So when I talk about
the energy transition

118
00:05:57,870 --> 00:06:00,700
or reducing carbon
emissions, as administrator,

119
00:06:00,700 --> 00:06:03,460
I'm not advocating for
any particular position.

120
00:06:03,460 --> 00:06:06,240
But again, I'm looking at it
from an analytic perspective

121
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:08,820
and what we need to do to
understand where the energy

122
00:06:08,820 --> 00:06:11,370
system is headed.

123
00:06:11,370 --> 00:06:15,190
We do maintain a comprehensive
energy statistics program.

124
00:06:15,190 --> 00:06:18,160
So by virtue of being
a statistical agency,

125
00:06:18,160 --> 00:06:20,910
we're vested with the
authority by Congress

126
00:06:20,910 --> 00:06:23,740
to collect data from
the energy industry.

127
00:06:23,740 --> 00:06:27,480
And so we do have a
comprehensive survey program.

128
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:30,330
Our energy supply survey
program represents

129
00:06:30,330 --> 00:06:32,320
our largest operational area.

130
00:06:32,320 --> 00:06:36,060
And we produce hundreds of
reports that rely on that data

131
00:06:36,060 --> 00:06:38,260
that we're collecting
from the supply side.

132
00:06:38,260 --> 00:06:40,530
On the demand
side, we have three

133
00:06:40,530 --> 00:06:43,080
large multi-year
consumption surveys

134
00:06:43,080 --> 00:06:46,480
that cover commercial
buildings, residential homes,

135
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:50,640
as well as the
manufacturing sector.

136
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:52,840
I'm going to breeze
through these very quickly,

137
00:06:52,840 --> 00:06:55,500
but I just want to give you a
sense of the comprehensiveness

138
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:57,240
of the data that we collect.

139
00:06:57,240 --> 00:07:02,070
So this is just looking at
electricity, electricity data.

140
00:07:02,070 --> 00:07:06,330
It starts with natural
resources on the right hand

141
00:07:06,330 --> 00:07:08,370
side, the primary energy.

142
00:07:08,370 --> 00:07:11,250
We look at electricity
generation and markets,

143
00:07:11,250 --> 00:07:14,190
and then, ultimately,
the sale of electricity

144
00:07:14,190 --> 00:07:17,050
to end use customers.

145
00:07:17,050 --> 00:07:19,390
We collect a lot of
electricity data.

146
00:07:19,390 --> 00:07:21,610
Much of it is on
an hourly basis.

147
00:07:21,610 --> 00:07:23,770
So this is a really
high volume of data.

148
00:07:23,770 --> 00:07:28,410
And we want to make that data
as accessible to the public

149
00:07:28,410 --> 00:07:29,110
as we can.

150
00:07:29,110 --> 00:07:30,760
So we've developed dashboards.

151
00:07:30,760 --> 00:07:33,750
You've probably, if
you work with our data,

152
00:07:33,750 --> 00:07:36,700
you've probably seen our
hourly electric grid monitor.

153
00:07:36,700 --> 00:07:38,550
It's been out for a
few years, but you

154
00:07:38,550 --> 00:07:43,000
can look at generation data
by balancing authority.

155
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:45,850
And on the right hand
side, earlier this year,

156
00:07:45,850 --> 00:07:48,640
we released the wholesale
electricity market portal.

157
00:07:48,640 --> 00:07:51,610
So this is data
coming from the RTOs.

158
00:07:51,610 --> 00:07:54,620
And you can look at the
same kind of information,

159
00:07:54,620 --> 00:07:57,880
including generation, but
also price information coming

160
00:07:57,880 --> 00:07:59,920
from the RTOs.

161
00:07:59,920 --> 00:08:03,550
We also, again, this is just
another example of our petroleum

162
00:08:03,550 --> 00:08:05,440
collection program.

163
00:08:05,440 --> 00:08:08,560
It's our surveys, everywhere
you see a pink box

164
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:11,290
with an EIA dash number,
that's a survey that we

165
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:12,350
have out in the field.

166
00:08:12,350 --> 00:08:14,890
So we're covering the
whole supply chain.

167
00:08:14,890 --> 00:08:18,250
We're looking at movements,
prices, sales, and trade

168
00:08:18,250 --> 00:08:21,590
of petroleum across the system.

169
00:08:21,590 --> 00:08:24,070
We have a similar
survey collection

170
00:08:24,070 --> 00:08:25,760
system for natural gas.

171
00:08:25,760 --> 00:08:28,390
Again, this is just to give
you a sense of the data

172
00:08:28,390 --> 00:08:30,020
that we collect.

173
00:08:30,020 --> 00:08:33,500
We also have a variety
of analytic products.

174
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:37,010
We have a short-term energy
outlook that we produce monthly.

175
00:08:37,010 --> 00:08:39,669
We actually just released
the latest one today.

176
00:08:39,669 --> 00:08:41,890
And there we use an
econometric model

177
00:08:41,890 --> 00:08:48,700
to forecast where we see US and
global energy markets headed

178
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:51,230
over the next 12 to 24 months.

179
00:08:51,230 --> 00:08:53,950
The forecast horizon is
always through the end

180
00:08:53,950 --> 00:08:57,190
of the following year.

181
00:08:57,190 --> 00:09:00,050
We also produce the
annual energy outlook.

182
00:09:00,050 --> 00:09:03,710
There we're looking at US
energy supply, consumption,

183
00:09:03,710 --> 00:09:06,030
and trade over a 30-year period.

184
00:09:06,030 --> 00:09:09,320
And we use a model called the
National Energy Modeling System

185
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:09,960
or NEMS.

186
00:09:09,960 --> 00:09:13,010
And I'm going to talk a
fair amount about the AEO

187
00:09:13,010 --> 00:09:15,320
and the NEMS model
in this presentation.

188
00:09:15,320 --> 00:09:18,620
We also produce an
international energy outlook.

189
00:09:18,620 --> 00:09:22,440
Has the same-- covers
the same kind of topics,

190
00:09:22,440 --> 00:09:24,865
but it's international in scale.

191
00:09:24,865 --> 00:09:26,490
And for that, we use
a different model.

192
00:09:26,490 --> 00:09:30,060
We use something called the
World Energy Projection System.

193
00:09:30,060 --> 00:09:33,390
We also produce a variety of
other reports and analyses.

194
00:09:33,390 --> 00:09:36,140
So for example,
Today in Energy, we

195
00:09:36,140 --> 00:09:38,780
publish a little piece
every day that covers

196
00:09:38,780 --> 00:09:41,810
some topical issue in energy.

197
00:09:41,810 --> 00:09:44,030
And then there's a
variety of reports

198
00:09:44,030 --> 00:09:50,107
that we produce to respond to
Congress or key stakeholders.

199
00:09:50,107 --> 00:09:51,940
I want to talk a little
bit about the energy

200
00:09:51,940 --> 00:09:55,310
transition, which is really
already under underway here.

201
00:09:55,310 --> 00:09:59,710
So this is looking at US
primary energy consumption

202
00:09:59,710 --> 00:10:02,572
going all the way back to 1940.

203
00:10:02,572 --> 00:10:04,030
And you've probably
seen this graph

204
00:10:04,030 --> 00:10:07,250
or you've heard elements, heard
about elements of this graph.

205
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:09,310
The thing that stands
out to me is just

206
00:10:09,310 --> 00:10:12,560
this rapid decline in coal
over the last two decades.

207
00:10:12,560 --> 00:10:18,620
But you can also see a rapid
rise in natural gas consumption.

208
00:10:18,620 --> 00:10:22,600
You can see that renewables, the
green line, particularly wind

209
00:10:22,600 --> 00:10:27,160
and solar, have
been on the rise.

210
00:10:27,160 --> 00:10:29,270
If we zoom in on the
electricity sector,

211
00:10:29,270 --> 00:10:31,820
that's where a lot of these
changes are taking place.

212
00:10:31,820 --> 00:10:33,620
And you see the
same basic pattern.

213
00:10:33,620 --> 00:10:37,960
You see that decline in
coal-fired generation, the rise

214
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:39,880
in both natural
gas-fired generation

215
00:10:39,880 --> 00:10:42,230
as well as zero
carbon generation.

216
00:10:42,230 --> 00:10:45,280
And again, a big portion
of that rise in zero carbon

217
00:10:45,280 --> 00:10:49,240
is from wind and solar.

218
00:10:49,240 --> 00:10:52,390
We can also take a
very zoomed in view

219
00:10:52,390 --> 00:10:54,740
of where we are currently.

220
00:10:54,740 --> 00:10:56,270
So this is a Sankey diagram.

221
00:10:56,270 --> 00:10:59,590
We actually released this
just a couple of weeks ago

222
00:10:59,590 --> 00:11:02,660
and gives you more
details on energy flows.

223
00:11:02,660 --> 00:11:04,730
So if you start on
the left hand side,

224
00:11:04,730 --> 00:11:08,390
these are sources
of primary energy.

225
00:11:08,390 --> 00:11:13,370
And as you move to
the right hand side,

226
00:11:13,370 --> 00:11:17,840
you're seeing those sources of
energy enter the end use sector.

227
00:11:17,840 --> 00:11:22,900
So the Sankey diagram is
looking at energy consumption

228
00:11:22,900 --> 00:11:24,603
by source and sector.

229
00:11:24,603 --> 00:11:26,020
You can see that
in the middle, we

230
00:11:26,020 --> 00:11:30,580
have the transformation of
these primary energy sources

231
00:11:30,580 --> 00:11:33,560
into both electricity
and waste heat.

232
00:11:33,560 --> 00:11:37,660
So the thing that we did in this
version of the Sankey diagram

233
00:11:37,660 --> 00:11:40,120
is for the thermal sources,
for the natural gas, coal,

234
00:11:40,120 --> 00:11:42,010
and nuclear, you
can actually see

235
00:11:42,010 --> 00:11:46,780
the split between useful
electricity generation and then

236
00:11:46,780 --> 00:11:50,900
the portion that goes to
waste heat on the bottom

237
00:11:50,900 --> 00:11:55,340
here in this black,
this black bar.

238
00:11:55,340 --> 00:11:59,580
So if you think about it,
right, if we can grow--

239
00:11:59,580 --> 00:12:02,660
if we grow renewables,
there we're

240
00:12:02,660 --> 00:12:04,170
assuming a one to
one conversion.

241
00:12:04,170 --> 00:12:07,430
So one unit of
renewable electricity

242
00:12:07,430 --> 00:12:09,720
equals one unit
of primary energy.

243
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:13,620
But we have all these thermal
losses from the thermal sources.

244
00:12:13,620 --> 00:12:17,490
So if renewables continue
to grow, all else equal,

245
00:12:17,490 --> 00:12:20,060
we could potentially shrink
the amount of primary energy

246
00:12:20,060 --> 00:12:22,500
we need to meet our end
use service demands.

247
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:25,950
Now, as you move to the right
into the end use sectors,

248
00:12:25,950 --> 00:12:28,250
the way that we draw the
boundary on this diagram

249
00:12:28,250 --> 00:12:33,020
is it's fuels that
are being consumed

250
00:12:33,020 --> 00:12:36,740
by demand devices that
ultimately meet our end use

251
00:12:36,740 --> 00:12:37,860
service demands.

252
00:12:37,860 --> 00:12:40,340
So you have fuels
moving to devices

253
00:12:40,340 --> 00:12:45,510
like furnaces, heat pumps,
vehicles, and being consumed.

254
00:12:45,510 --> 00:12:47,520
Obviously, within
each of those sectors,

255
00:12:47,520 --> 00:12:50,710
there are additional losses
associated with conversion.

256
00:12:50,710 --> 00:12:53,610
But we draw the
boundary before that.

257
00:12:53,610 --> 00:12:56,310
One of the things that I
like about this diagram

258
00:12:56,310 --> 00:12:59,400
is that it strips away a
lot of the technology detail

259
00:12:59,400 --> 00:13:01,660
that we're often accustomed
to thinking about.

260
00:13:01,660 --> 00:13:05,290
And we're just focused on
the current flow of energy.

261
00:13:05,290 --> 00:13:08,460
So if we're thinking about
the energy transition

262
00:13:08,460 --> 00:13:11,350
and reducing carbon emissions,
I mean, the way I see it,

263
00:13:11,350 --> 00:13:12,790
there's three basic options.

264
00:13:12,790 --> 00:13:14,530
They're not mutually
exclusive, right?

265
00:13:14,530 --> 00:13:18,310
But we can increase carbon
free electricity and fuels.

266
00:13:18,310 --> 00:13:20,940
We can decrease
final energy demands.

267
00:13:20,940 --> 00:13:24,790
Or we can do some form of
carbon dioxide removal.

268
00:13:24,790 --> 00:13:30,370
And the question is, this is
historical data that we collect.

269
00:13:30,370 --> 00:13:32,370
We have high confidence in this.

270
00:13:32,370 --> 00:13:35,470
But how do we advance this?

271
00:13:35,470 --> 00:13:39,840
How do-- what will this
look like in 2030 and 2050?

272
00:13:39,840 --> 00:13:43,920
And that's where energy
modeling comes in.

273
00:13:43,920 --> 00:13:46,540
So just to get us started
and talking about modeling.

274
00:13:46,540 --> 00:13:49,660
A lot of people quote George Box
who said, "All models are wrong;

275
00:13:49,660 --> 00:13:50,850
some are useful."

276
00:13:50,850 --> 00:13:54,290
I actually this quote
from Paul Krugman.

277
00:13:54,290 --> 00:13:56,190
This was in his New
York Times blog.

278
00:13:56,190 --> 00:13:59,520
He was actually talking about
models of the US economy.

279
00:13:59,520 --> 00:14:01,980
But it applies
universally to all models,

280
00:14:01,980 --> 00:14:03,420
including energy models.

281
00:14:03,420 --> 00:14:07,070
And what he said is models are
an enormously important tool

282
00:14:07,070 --> 00:14:08,580
for clarifying your thought.

283
00:14:08,580 --> 00:14:10,770
You don't have to literally
believe your model.

284
00:14:10,770 --> 00:14:14,180
In fact, you're a fool if you do
to believe that putting together

285
00:14:14,180 --> 00:14:17,150
a simplified but complete
account of how things work

286
00:14:17,150 --> 00:14:20,330
helps you gain a much more
sophisticated understanding

287
00:14:20,330 --> 00:14:21,800
of the real situation.

288
00:14:21,800 --> 00:14:23,810
People who don't
use models end up

289
00:14:23,810 --> 00:14:29,440
relying on slogans, all of which
are wrong some of the time.

290
00:14:29,440 --> 00:14:32,500
So models, energy
systems, they're

291
00:14:32,500 --> 00:14:35,780
too complicated for us to
develop, at least for me.

292
00:14:35,780 --> 00:14:38,500
I can't develop a mental
model of the energy system

293
00:14:38,500 --> 00:14:40,640
and project that forward.

294
00:14:40,640 --> 00:14:44,740
We need some way to organize
all of this information

295
00:14:44,740 --> 00:14:46,970
into a model.

296
00:14:46,970 --> 00:14:50,470
Models allow us to build the
self-consistent framework that

297
00:14:50,470 --> 00:14:53,950
allows us to systematically
explore the future decision

298
00:14:53,950 --> 00:14:54,770
space.

299
00:14:54,770 --> 00:14:57,080
So you can see the
schematic diagram here.

300
00:14:57,080 --> 00:15:01,030
I tend to think of models
in terms of layers.

301
00:15:01,030 --> 00:15:04,290
And this is meant to represent
just a generic energy system

302
00:15:04,290 --> 00:15:04,790
model.

303
00:15:04,790 --> 00:15:07,670
So on the left hand side,
you see model input data.

304
00:15:07,670 --> 00:15:10,072
We've got to go out and
gather some primary data.

305
00:15:10,072 --> 00:15:12,280
There's going to be some
intermediate transformations

306
00:15:12,280 --> 00:15:13,072
of that data.

307
00:15:13,072 --> 00:15:14,530
And then, ultimately,
there's going

308
00:15:14,530 --> 00:15:16,600
to be a final formatted
data set that's

309
00:15:16,600 --> 00:15:19,750
going to go that's going
to be fed into the model.

310
00:15:19,750 --> 00:15:22,000
On the right hand side, you
can see model structure.

311
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,370
And it all starts with
governing dynamics.

312
00:15:24,370 --> 00:15:26,290
What are the dynamics
that are actually

313
00:15:26,290 --> 00:15:30,060
going to drive decision
making in the model?

314
00:15:30,060 --> 00:15:31,950
Are you performing
an optimization?

315
00:15:31,950 --> 00:15:33,930
Is it a consumer choice model?

316
00:15:33,930 --> 00:15:36,500
Is it an agent based model,
some kind of simulation,

317
00:15:36,500 --> 00:15:37,880
system dynamics?

318
00:15:37,880 --> 00:15:40,100
You've got to pick some
governing dynamics.

319
00:15:40,100 --> 00:15:43,250
Below that, You've got to
take those governing dynamics

320
00:15:43,250 --> 00:15:47,130
and then encode them into a
mathematical representation.

321
00:15:47,130 --> 00:15:49,730
And then you have to take the
mathematical representation

322
00:15:49,730 --> 00:15:52,650
and then implement in code.

323
00:15:52,650 --> 00:15:54,620
And then, ultimately,
you run the model

324
00:15:54,620 --> 00:15:57,870
and it pulls the data
and the code together.

325
00:15:57,870 --> 00:15:59,910
The model gets
instantiated, it runs,

326
00:15:59,910 --> 00:16:03,300
and then it produces output
that we look at and analyze.

327
00:16:03,300 --> 00:16:05,060
So there's a very
systematic approach

328
00:16:05,060 --> 00:16:07,830
to the practice of modeling.

329
00:16:07,830 --> 00:16:10,800
So at EIA, to do our
domestic outlook,

330
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:13,710
we use something called the
National Energy Modeling System.

331
00:16:13,710 --> 00:16:18,810
And each of the boxes here
represent a separate module.

332
00:16:18,810 --> 00:16:20,300
So on the left
hand side, you can

333
00:16:20,300 --> 00:16:23,160
see these are sources
of primary energy.

334
00:16:23,160 --> 00:16:26,280
So I showed you all that
survey data that we collect.

335
00:16:26,280 --> 00:16:28,190
A lot of that survey
data is actually

336
00:16:28,190 --> 00:16:34,760
being used to populate the
input data sets for the model

337
00:16:34,760 --> 00:16:35,880
and to calibrate.

338
00:16:35,880 --> 00:16:38,700
You can see on the right hand
side a bunch of orange boxes.

339
00:16:38,700 --> 00:16:40,380
Those are the end use sectors.

340
00:16:40,380 --> 00:16:43,890
So those three big consumption
surveys that I mentioned,

341
00:16:43,890 --> 00:16:48,140
they're being used to develop
the input data for the end use

342
00:16:48,140 --> 00:16:49,220
sectors.

343
00:16:49,220 --> 00:16:52,770
Along the bottom here, we have
intermediate transformations.

344
00:16:52,770 --> 00:16:55,760
And then along the top
we've got carbon management,

345
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:58,220
macro activity, and
then other drivers

346
00:16:58,220 --> 00:16:59,960
like international
energy and trade,

347
00:16:59,960 --> 00:17:02,170
and emissions policy,
which, of course, are

348
00:17:02,170 --> 00:17:03,900
going to affect the outcome.

349
00:17:03,900 --> 00:17:06,869
And then we need a way to pull
all these modules together.

350
00:17:06,869 --> 00:17:10,010
So we have an integrating
module that basically iterates

351
00:17:10,010 --> 00:17:14,480
through all of these modules
and finds a price quantity

352
00:17:14,480 --> 00:17:19,770
equilibrium between all
of these various modules.

353
00:17:19,770 --> 00:17:21,569
OK, so we've got
this great model.

354
00:17:21,569 --> 00:17:22,869
And sophisticated.

355
00:17:22,869 --> 00:17:24,660
What are we going to do with it?

356
00:17:24,660 --> 00:17:26,490
And the first
question you might ask

357
00:17:26,490 --> 00:17:29,890
is, should we use these
models to produce a forecast?

358
00:17:29,890 --> 00:17:33,030
And by forecast, what
I mean is, should we

359
00:17:33,030 --> 00:17:34,800
use the model to
make a prediction

360
00:17:34,800 --> 00:17:37,720
about a specific
quantity in the future.

361
00:17:37,720 --> 00:17:40,110
And I think the answer
for me to that question

362
00:17:40,110 --> 00:17:42,930
is no, we should not do that.

363
00:17:42,930 --> 00:17:45,720
And my thinking on
this was heavily

364
00:17:45,720 --> 00:17:48,850
influenced by this report
by Hodges in [? DOER. ?]

365
00:17:48,850 --> 00:17:50,830
It was published in 1992.

366
00:17:50,830 --> 00:17:53,580
They were researchers at
RAND, and they were actually

367
00:17:53,580 --> 00:17:55,062
focused on military models.

368
00:17:55,062 --> 00:17:56,520
They were thinking
about everything

369
00:17:56,520 --> 00:18:01,830
from models of fuze activation
to simulations of theater level

370
00:18:01,830 --> 00:18:02,740
combat.

371
00:18:02,740 --> 00:18:05,820
And there was a lot of
confusion about, well,

372
00:18:05,820 --> 00:18:08,850
can we use these models
to forecast and so forth.

373
00:18:08,850 --> 00:18:12,420
And their point was,
if you're using a model

374
00:18:12,420 --> 00:18:14,400
to produce a forecast,
it ought to come

375
00:18:14,400 --> 00:18:17,063
with some kind of
a warranty, right?

376
00:18:17,063 --> 00:18:18,480
Otherwise, why am
I going to trust

377
00:18:18,480 --> 00:18:20,320
the forecast or the prediction.

378
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:22,040
Well, how do you
produce a warranty?

379
00:18:22,040 --> 00:18:24,560
You have to be able
to validate the model.

380
00:18:24,560 --> 00:18:26,950
You have to be able
to take the model,

381
00:18:26,950 --> 00:18:29,260
produce some kind of
a forecast, compare it

382
00:18:29,260 --> 00:18:31,610
against real world
results, and then say, OK,

383
00:18:31,610 --> 00:18:32,720
how accurate is it?

384
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:34,930
And they said, OK.

385
00:18:34,930 --> 00:18:37,990
So if you want to forecast the
model should be validatable.

386
00:18:37,990 --> 00:18:40,130
Well, how do if your
model is validatable?

387
00:18:40,130 --> 00:18:42,590
They lay out four
different conditions here.

388
00:18:42,590 --> 00:18:45,610
The first is it's got to be
possible to observe and measure

389
00:18:45,610 --> 00:18:47,060
the situation being modeled.

390
00:18:47,060 --> 00:18:48,120
It's pretty obvious.

391
00:18:48,120 --> 00:18:50,530
Second, the situation
being modeled

392
00:18:50,530 --> 00:18:54,100
must exhibit a constancy
of structure and time.

393
00:18:54,100 --> 00:18:56,440
Third, the situation
being modeled

394
00:18:56,440 --> 00:19:00,310
must exhibit constancy across
variations in conditions

395
00:19:00,310 --> 00:19:02,390
not specified in the model.

396
00:19:02,390 --> 00:19:04,570
And then fourth, you have
to collect enough data

397
00:19:04,570 --> 00:19:06,350
to make the predictive test.

398
00:19:06,350 --> 00:19:10,420
And when you think about long
term models of the energy

399
00:19:10,420 --> 00:19:14,160
system, they fail on
conditions two and three.

400
00:19:14,160 --> 00:19:18,570
The structure of energy markets,
they do change over time.

401
00:19:18,570 --> 00:19:21,810
And we often-- models
of the energy system

402
00:19:21,810 --> 00:19:23,020
are highly simplified.

403
00:19:23,020 --> 00:19:26,850
So we're not they can change
across variations that we're not

404
00:19:26,850 --> 00:19:28,000
modeling, right?

405
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:33,160
So I would argue that we can't
really validate these models.

406
00:19:33,160 --> 00:19:36,077
And so we shouldn't be
using them to forecast.

407
00:19:36,077 --> 00:19:38,160
The other thing that I've
just observed in my time

408
00:19:38,160 --> 00:19:40,560
as an energy modeler,
is because we

409
00:19:40,560 --> 00:19:44,460
can't validate these
long term projections,

410
00:19:44,460 --> 00:19:46,920
there's really no
guideposts there

411
00:19:46,920 --> 00:19:50,500
to determine if I add some
new complexity to my model,

412
00:19:50,500 --> 00:19:54,520
does it actually add value, does
it give me more insight or not.

413
00:19:54,520 --> 00:19:57,960
And so my observation
is a lot of these models

414
00:19:57,960 --> 00:20:02,760
have simply gotten
more complex over time,

415
00:20:02,760 --> 00:20:06,730
as people try and analyze many
of these issues in more detail.

416
00:20:06,730 --> 00:20:08,730
But we don't really know
whether that complexity

417
00:20:08,730 --> 00:20:12,380
is buying us more insight.

418
00:20:12,380 --> 00:20:15,790
When models are used
to produce forecasts,

419
00:20:15,790 --> 00:20:18,002
the results are
generally pretty dismal.

420
00:20:18,002 --> 00:20:19,460
So these are just
two examples that

421
00:20:19,460 --> 00:20:20,940
are drawn from the literature.

422
00:20:20,940 --> 00:20:23,900
The one on the left is the
US Atomic Energy Commission.

423
00:20:23,900 --> 00:20:26,360
This is a forecast
from 1962 looking

424
00:20:26,360 --> 00:20:28,500
at installed nuclear capacity.

425
00:20:28,500 --> 00:20:32,010
The vertical-- yeah, the
vertical axis's log scale,

426
00:20:32,010 --> 00:20:34,400
they were off by an
order of magnitude.

427
00:20:34,400 --> 00:20:37,880
The one on the right
were a set of predictions

428
00:20:37,880 --> 00:20:40,430
about what primary
energy consumption would

429
00:20:40,430 --> 00:20:43,340
be in the year 2000.

430
00:20:43,340 --> 00:20:47,060
And every single
study overestimated

431
00:20:47,060 --> 00:20:48,740
what-- nobody under
predicted what

432
00:20:48,740 --> 00:20:50,430
energy consumption would be.

433
00:20:50,430 --> 00:20:52,560
And I want you to
remember this example,

434
00:20:52,560 --> 00:20:56,630
because I'm going to show you
some results from EIA that

435
00:20:56,630 --> 00:20:59,140
exhibit the same
basic phenomenon.

436
00:20:59,140 --> 00:21:02,100
OK?

437
00:21:02,100 --> 00:21:03,630
Computer went to sleep.

438
00:21:03,630 --> 00:21:06,330
So keep this in mind
because I'm going

439
00:21:06,330 --> 00:21:08,370
to show you the results
that are going to follow

440
00:21:08,370 --> 00:21:09,580
the same basic pattern.

441
00:21:09,580 --> 00:21:13,570
We often anchor on what's
happening currently,

442
00:21:13,570 --> 00:21:16,290
and we're not creative
enough about where things

443
00:21:16,290 --> 00:21:18,140
might be headed in the future.

444
00:21:18,140 --> 00:21:21,830

445
00:21:21,830 --> 00:21:25,220
So shouldn't really
use models for--

446
00:21:25,220 --> 00:21:27,030
these kind of models
for forecasting.

447
00:21:27,030 --> 00:21:28,470
But what can we use them for?

448
00:21:28,470 --> 00:21:29,428
What are they good for?

449
00:21:29,428 --> 00:21:32,780
There's still lots of really
valuable uses for these models.

450
00:21:32,780 --> 00:21:36,560
They can simply be an aid in
helping us think and hypothesize

451
00:21:36,560 --> 00:21:38,610
about the future of energy.

452
00:21:38,610 --> 00:21:40,760
They can help us
create a dialogue

453
00:21:40,760 --> 00:21:42,990
among different stakeholders
on complex issues.

454
00:21:42,990 --> 00:21:45,365
I mean, if we're thinking
about something like the energy

455
00:21:45,365 --> 00:21:47,490
transition and we want
to start a dialogue,

456
00:21:47,490 --> 00:21:50,070
there has to be some basis
for the dialogue, right?

457
00:21:50,070 --> 00:21:52,610
So if you have a systematic
representation of the energy

458
00:21:52,610 --> 00:21:55,710
system that you can
advance into the future,

459
00:21:55,710 --> 00:21:57,890
we can start to have a
debate about the model

460
00:21:57,890 --> 00:21:59,720
and what it means and so forth.

461
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:02,880
We can identify key system
features and effects,

462
00:22:02,880 --> 00:22:04,490
pitfalls, and trade offs, right?

463
00:22:04,490 --> 00:22:06,890
That's where a lot of the
insight from this modeling work

464
00:22:06,890 --> 00:22:07,810
comes from.

465
00:22:07,810 --> 00:22:10,820
We can also identify key sources
of uncertainty and knowledge

466
00:22:10,820 --> 00:22:11,370
gaps.

467
00:22:11,370 --> 00:22:13,370
It might turn out that
the model is particularly

468
00:22:13,370 --> 00:22:15,320
sensitive to
assumptions we're making

469
00:22:15,320 --> 00:22:18,060
about a specific
technology or sector,

470
00:22:18,060 --> 00:22:19,880
but maybe we lack
the data to feel

471
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:23,720
confident about
how we're modeling

472
00:22:23,720 --> 00:22:25,320
that piece of the system.

473
00:22:25,320 --> 00:22:27,860
And then, finally, you
can use models to help

474
00:22:27,860 --> 00:22:29,520
inform decision strategies.

475
00:22:29,520 --> 00:22:31,560
I know there's a bunch
of future uncertainty.

476
00:22:31,560 --> 00:22:33,360
I don't know what's
going to happen.

477
00:22:33,360 --> 00:22:36,530
But I can incorporate that
uncertainty into my model

478
00:22:36,530 --> 00:22:41,000
and help me come up
with a path forward.

479
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:42,890
This idea that
models should not be

480
00:22:42,890 --> 00:22:46,160
used to produce forecasts
or precise projections,

481
00:22:46,160 --> 00:22:48,320
they should be used for
insight, is an idea that's

482
00:22:48,320 --> 00:22:50,610
been around a really long time.

483
00:22:50,610 --> 00:22:53,180
So I want to give credit to the
folks at the Stanford Energy

484
00:22:53,180 --> 00:22:57,180
Modeling Forum who are making
this point four decades ago.

485
00:22:57,180 --> 00:23:01,140
I also really like the quote
at the bottom by Bill Hogan.

486
00:23:01,140 --> 00:23:03,380
It's not the individual
results of a model

487
00:23:03,380 --> 00:23:04,590
that are so important.

488
00:23:04,590 --> 00:23:06,890
It's the improved
user appreciation

489
00:23:06,890 --> 00:23:09,020
of the policy problem
that is the greatest

490
00:23:09,020 --> 00:23:12,150
contribution to modeling.

491
00:23:12,150 --> 00:23:12,650
All right.

492
00:23:12,650 --> 00:23:18,230
So I want to talk a little
bit about some past surprises.

493
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:21,370
There have been some
energy market developments

494
00:23:21,370 --> 00:23:27,110
that have taken not just EIA,
but many analysts by surprise.

495
00:23:27,110 --> 00:23:31,830
And I want to talk through
those a little bit.

496
00:23:31,830 --> 00:23:33,690
Before I do that, I
do want to mention

497
00:23:33,690 --> 00:23:40,080
that EIA does produce an AEO
retrospective report every two

498
00:23:40,080 --> 00:23:40,990
years.

499
00:23:40,990 --> 00:23:45,390
It compares the results from our
reference case against realized

500
00:23:45,390 --> 00:23:49,920
outcomes, and it's really just
focused on statistical measures.

501
00:23:49,920 --> 00:23:53,170
Things like percent difference,
average percent difference,

