715
00:34:10,380 --> 00:34:14,150
The other thing is that I think
that judgments about model

716
00:34:14,150 --> 00:34:16,860
calibration, how we design
scenarios and so forth,

717
00:34:16,860 --> 00:34:19,400
are affected by
cognitive heuristics.

718
00:34:19,400 --> 00:34:23,540
If you haven't heard of
cognitive heuristics before,

719
00:34:23,540 --> 00:34:25,699
heuristics are just
mental shortcuts

720
00:34:25,699 --> 00:34:28,670
that can facilitate problem
solving and probability

721
00:34:28,670 --> 00:34:29,840
judgments.

722
00:34:29,840 --> 00:34:33,320
This literature goes all the
way back to Kahneman and Tversky

723
00:34:33,320 --> 00:34:34,830
in 1974.

724
00:34:34,830 --> 00:34:37,429
But there's two heuristics
that I think really

725
00:34:37,429 --> 00:34:39,790
matter for energy modeling.

726
00:34:39,790 --> 00:34:41,730
One is the
availability heuristic,

727
00:34:41,730 --> 00:34:44,639
that people assess the
probabilities of a future event

728
00:34:44,639 --> 00:34:48,060
or outcome on the basis of
how easily they can remember

729
00:34:48,060 --> 00:34:50,940
past examples, or
how easily they can

730
00:34:50,940 --> 00:34:52,960
envision future possibilities.

731
00:34:52,960 --> 00:34:56,639
And when you're focused
on the data that you have,

732
00:34:56,639 --> 00:34:58,980
that's what's available
to you, and you're going

733
00:34:58,980 --> 00:35:00,580
to make use of that heuristic.

734
00:35:00,580 --> 00:35:02,580
The other is anchoring
and adjustment,

735
00:35:02,580 --> 00:35:05,250
that people will often
start with an initial value

736
00:35:05,250 --> 00:35:07,180
and they tend to anchor on it.

737
00:35:07,180 --> 00:35:09,480
And even when you get
additional information

738
00:35:09,480 --> 00:35:13,920
to move you off that anchor,
the adjustment off of the anchor

739
00:35:13,920 --> 00:35:15,250
is often insufficient.

740
00:35:15,250 --> 00:35:17,010
We don't make big
enough adjustments

741
00:35:17,010 --> 00:35:20,370
once we learn new things.

742
00:35:20,370 --> 00:35:21,900
And I think these
heuristics can be

743
00:35:21,900 --> 00:35:24,570
hard to overcome,
particularly in an environment

744
00:35:24,570 --> 00:35:27,340
where modelers can be judged
for errant projections.

745
00:35:27,340 --> 00:35:31,090
If I'm going to be wrong,
and I get what happened?

746
00:35:31,090 --> 00:35:34,180
I'd rather be able to say, look,
this is the data that I had.

747
00:35:34,180 --> 00:35:38,070
This was the best guess I
possibly could make at the time.

748
00:35:38,070 --> 00:35:40,650
It takes some courage
to really say, well,

749
00:35:40,650 --> 00:35:42,400
it really could
grow exponentially.

750
00:35:42,400 --> 00:35:44,110
Let's run a case
that looks like that.

751
00:35:44,110 --> 00:35:48,090
And the thing I want
to emphasize is at EIA,

752
00:35:48,090 --> 00:35:50,810
we're trying to be as
transparent as we can.

753
00:35:50,810 --> 00:35:52,410
We have nothing to hide.

754
00:35:52,410 --> 00:35:55,360
And the things I'm talking
about here, these heuristics,

755
00:35:55,360 --> 00:35:56,830
this isn't limited to EIA.

756
00:35:56,830 --> 00:35:58,930
This is like a
universal phenomena.

757
00:35:58,930 --> 00:36:01,780
This is happening with
modeling all over the place.

758
00:36:01,780 --> 00:36:06,390
And I'm just using EIA work
as an example to illustrate.

759
00:36:06,390 --> 00:36:10,210
OK, so what can we
do about uncertainty?

760
00:36:10,210 --> 00:36:15,440
In the process of overhauling
our long-term modeling program,

761
00:36:15,440 --> 00:36:18,290
I spent a lot of time going
back to this National Research

762
00:36:18,290 --> 00:36:20,880
Council report that
was released in 1992,

763
00:36:20,880 --> 00:36:23,570
and they really emphasized
the importance of uncertainty.

764
00:36:23,570 --> 00:36:26,610
That uncertainty is inherent
in the nature of models.

765
00:36:26,610 --> 00:36:29,310
And we shouldn't just
ignore it or eliminate it.

766
00:36:29,310 --> 00:36:31,470
We need to find ways--

767
00:36:31,470 --> 00:36:34,220
EIA needs to find
ways to incorporate

768
00:36:34,220 --> 00:36:38,490
the consideration of uncertainty
into NEMS explicitly.

769
00:36:38,490 --> 00:36:43,280
And the whole report was based
around recommendations for EIA

770
00:36:43,280 --> 00:36:44,707
to build and run NEMS.

771
00:36:44,707 --> 00:36:46,290
So they thought it
was very important.

772
00:36:46,290 --> 00:36:47,600
I think it's very important.

773
00:36:47,600 --> 00:36:49,250
And to me the
question comes down

774
00:36:49,250 --> 00:36:52,580
to how do you illuminate and
inform future energy pathways

775
00:36:52,580 --> 00:36:54,450
given all of this uncertainty?

776
00:36:54,450 --> 00:36:58,220
And I think it really depends
on the specific question you're

777
00:36:58,220 --> 00:36:59,070
trying to ask.

778
00:36:59,070 --> 00:37:01,430
There's not like one method
that you should always

779
00:37:01,430 --> 00:37:02,802
use to assess uncertainty.

780
00:37:02,802 --> 00:37:04,760
It really depends on the
nature of the question

781
00:37:04,760 --> 00:37:06,320
that you're asking.

782
00:37:06,320 --> 00:37:07,880
The other thing is
that I think it's

783
00:37:07,880 --> 00:37:11,970
helpful to break down
uncertainty into two categories.

784
00:37:11,970 --> 00:37:14,550
There's parametric
uncertainty, and that's

785
00:37:14,550 --> 00:37:16,830
uncertainty in the
input parameters

786
00:37:16,830 --> 00:37:18,820
that we put into our models.

787
00:37:18,820 --> 00:37:21,753
So I talked about wind
and solar capital costs.

788
00:37:21,753 --> 00:37:24,420
We have to make some assumption
about what those costs are going

789
00:37:24,420 --> 00:37:27,930
to be out through 2050, right?

790
00:37:27,930 --> 00:37:29,880
That's parametric uncertainty.

791
00:37:29,880 --> 00:37:32,100
And we have a lot of
tools in the toolbox

792
00:37:32,100 --> 00:37:34,410
in order to try and
address the effects

793
00:37:34,410 --> 00:37:36,430
of parametric uncertainty.

794
00:37:36,430 --> 00:37:40,210
We can do scenario analysis,
parametric sensitivity analysis,

795
00:37:40,210 --> 00:37:41,830
we can do Monte
Carlo simulations.

796
00:37:41,830 --> 00:37:43,860
There's something called
a method of Morris

797
00:37:43,860 --> 00:37:47,460
that does a random walk in
the input parameter space.

798
00:37:47,460 --> 00:37:50,100
Stochastic
optimization or robust

799
00:37:50,100 --> 00:37:53,640
optimization if we're trying
to develop a decision strategy.

800
00:37:53,640 --> 00:37:56,770
The second category is
structural uncertainty,

801
00:37:56,770 --> 00:37:59,190
which refers to the imperfect
and incomplete nature

802
00:37:59,190 --> 00:38:01,630
of the equations
describing the system.

803
00:38:01,630 --> 00:38:05,250
So you've got this really
complex world out there, right?

804
00:38:05,250 --> 00:38:08,050
And you're trying to distill
that into a computer model.

805
00:38:08,050 --> 00:38:11,760
The equations that you come
up with to govern that system

806
00:38:11,760 --> 00:38:13,540
are going to be highly
simplified, right?

807
00:38:13,540 --> 00:38:15,576
That's structural uncertainty.

808
00:38:15,576 --> 00:38:17,955
And there's also ways
we can deal with this,

809
00:38:17,955 --> 00:38:19,330
although there's
been less of it,

810
00:38:19,330 --> 00:38:20,980
I would say, in the literature.

811
00:38:20,980 --> 00:38:24,130
But there can be alternative
formulations of the model,

812
00:38:24,130 --> 00:38:25,422
different equations.

813
00:38:25,422 --> 00:38:26,880
There's a technique
called modeling

814
00:38:26,880 --> 00:38:30,540
to generate alternatives that
I can talk more about later on,

815
00:38:30,540 --> 00:38:33,100
or just model
intercomparison exercises.

816
00:38:33,100 --> 00:38:36,010
Again, Stanford Energy Modeling
Forum does a great job.

817
00:38:36,010 --> 00:38:37,720
They get a bunch of
modelers together.

818
00:38:37,720 --> 00:38:39,100
The models are different.

819
00:38:39,100 --> 00:38:41,130
They focus all the
models on the same issue

820
00:38:41,130 --> 00:38:42,930
and then see what comes out.

821
00:38:42,930 --> 00:38:45,690
Why are there differences
in the outputs

822
00:38:45,690 --> 00:38:47,100
across these different models?

823
00:38:47,100 --> 00:38:51,910
So that's another way to
address structural uncertainty.

824
00:38:51,910 --> 00:38:54,790
We know that moving forward,
the system is already

825
00:38:54,790 --> 00:38:57,160
in a period of rapid transition.

826
00:38:57,160 --> 00:38:59,420
And when things are
changing rapidly,

827
00:38:59,420 --> 00:39:00,650
it heightens uncertainty.

828
00:39:00,650 --> 00:39:04,420
And I've just got a laundry
list of things that keep me up

829
00:39:04,420 --> 00:39:05,760
at night as a modeler.

830
00:39:05,760 --> 00:39:07,535
What are the impacts
of climate change?

831
00:39:07,535 --> 00:39:09,410
How is that going to
affect end user demands?

832
00:39:09,410 --> 00:39:11,743
What are the impacts of climate
change on infrastructure

833
00:39:11,743 --> 00:39:13,402
and renewable resources?

834
00:39:13,402 --> 00:39:15,610
How are we going to build
out all this infrastructure

835
00:39:15,610 --> 00:39:20,080
and develop new supply chains
for clean energy technology?

836
00:39:20,080 --> 00:39:22,510
I showed you examples with
technology innovation.

837
00:39:22,510 --> 00:39:25,430
At EIA, we underestimated
the role of wind and solar.

838
00:39:25,430 --> 00:39:27,010
What's going to
happen in the future?

839
00:39:27,010 --> 00:39:28,550
What about novel technologies?

840
00:39:28,550 --> 00:39:32,588
What about enhanced geothermal,
fusion, space based solar power?

841
00:39:32,588 --> 00:39:34,130
I mean, should those
be in the model?

842
00:39:34,130 --> 00:39:35,838
What if there's a
technology breakthrough

843
00:39:35,838 --> 00:39:37,990
and we're missing it?

844
00:39:37,990 --> 00:39:39,470
Electricity demand growth.

845
00:39:39,470 --> 00:39:41,600
There's a lot talk about
AI in data centers.

846
00:39:41,600 --> 00:39:44,560
Does that matter-- is that
going to matter or not?

847
00:39:44,560 --> 00:39:48,190
Or are we just going to improve
the efficiency of the chips

848
00:39:48,190 --> 00:39:50,210
so much that it's
not a big deal.

849
00:39:50,210 --> 00:39:52,430
I don't know.

850
00:39:52,430 --> 00:39:54,988
Again, I've talked about
the role of policy.

851
00:39:54,988 --> 00:39:57,030
If there's significant
changes in infrastructure,

852
00:39:57,030 --> 00:39:58,583
what's the impact on people?

853
00:39:58,583 --> 00:40:00,750
And then, of course, there
are the unknown unknowns.

854
00:40:00,750 --> 00:40:02,625
There are the things
that I can't conceive of

855
00:40:02,625 --> 00:40:05,780
to put on this list but are
probably going to happen

856
00:40:05,780 --> 00:40:07,980
and we're going to
be dealing with.

857
00:40:07,980 --> 00:40:10,370
So the bottom line
is we need to find

858
00:40:10,370 --> 00:40:14,430
ways to deal with uncertainty.

859
00:40:14,430 --> 00:40:17,890
Now, I want to talk a little bit
about what we're doing at EIA.

860
00:40:17,890 --> 00:40:22,010
This example is specific to EIA.

861
00:40:22,010 --> 00:40:24,240
So we developed something
called the reference case.

862
00:40:24,240 --> 00:40:26,130
I've mentioned this a few times.

863
00:40:26,130 --> 00:40:28,980
And people tend to
interpret our reference case

864
00:40:28,980 --> 00:40:31,260
as though it is a forecast.

865
00:40:31,260 --> 00:40:33,610
This goes back to AEO 2022.

866
00:40:33,610 --> 00:40:35,190
This was before I joined.

867
00:40:35,190 --> 00:40:36,910
And you can see on
the left hand side,

868
00:40:36,910 --> 00:40:39,700
I think we define it-- the way
it's defined is exactly right,

869
00:40:39,700 --> 00:40:43,380
that it's a baseline for
comparison between side cases

870
00:40:43,380 --> 00:40:45,570
to explain alternative trends.

871
00:40:45,570 --> 00:40:49,020
But on the right hand
side, 70% of the figures

872
00:40:49,020 --> 00:40:53,420
that appeared in that AEO show
the reference case by itself.

873
00:40:53,420 --> 00:40:56,200
So if you're just reading it
casually, you're going to think,

874
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:58,210
hey, this looks like
a forecast, right?

875
00:40:58,210 --> 00:41:01,020
And I think that that's
really problematic.

876
00:41:01,020 --> 00:41:03,420
I think as a modeler,
we never, never want

877
00:41:03,420 --> 00:41:07,650
to put a single result or
the results from a single run

878
00:41:07,650 --> 00:41:09,830
onto a figure.

879
00:41:09,830 --> 00:41:11,890
Just think about it
mathematically, right?

880
00:41:11,890 --> 00:41:14,240
Even if the reference
case was our best guess,

881
00:41:14,240 --> 00:41:17,620
the probability of realizing a
single trajectory for anything

882
00:41:17,620 --> 00:41:22,800
through a continuous solution
space is going to be zero.

883
00:41:22,800 --> 00:41:25,890
In AEO 2023, we really
tried to emphasize again

884
00:41:25,890 --> 00:41:28,360
the range of results
across the cases.

885
00:41:28,360 --> 00:41:30,780
So this is looking at
electricity generation

886
00:41:30,780 --> 00:41:32,380
by select technologies.

887
00:41:32,380 --> 00:41:34,650
We're still showing
the reference case

888
00:41:34,650 --> 00:41:36,330
as that black line,
but you can now

889
00:41:36,330 --> 00:41:40,860
see that there's a gray band
around every reference case

890
00:41:40,860 --> 00:41:44,060
result. And that shows the
range around the reference case.

891
00:41:44,060 --> 00:41:45,820
So we're trying
to emphasize, hey,

892
00:41:45,820 --> 00:41:47,620
there is a range
of outcomes here.

893
00:41:47,620 --> 00:41:50,550
We don't know for sure
what's going to happen.

894
00:41:50,550 --> 00:41:53,610
The other thing, we're
also experimenting

895
00:41:53,610 --> 00:41:54,550
with other methods.

896
00:41:54,550 --> 00:41:57,570
This is something that we
did publish in the AEO.

897
00:41:57,570 --> 00:42:00,870
This is looking at
energy-related carbon dioxide

898
00:42:00,870 --> 00:42:01,810
emissions.

899
00:42:01,810 --> 00:42:03,750
And we actually
utilized an approach

900
00:42:03,750 --> 00:42:06,760
that was published by
[? Kac ?] et al. in 2017,

901
00:42:06,760 --> 00:42:08,350
and it was directed to EIA.

902
00:42:08,350 --> 00:42:10,370
They took our--
they took the AEO

903
00:42:10,370 --> 00:42:12,280
and they built these
uncertainty cones.

904
00:42:12,280 --> 00:42:14,700
And we decided,
hey, let's actually

905
00:42:14,700 --> 00:42:16,370
build this into the AEO.

906
00:42:16,370 --> 00:42:16,870
All right.

907
00:42:16,870 --> 00:42:20,100
So what do we do--
what do you do here?

908
00:42:20,100 --> 00:42:23,800
For a given projection
horizon, let's say five years

909
00:42:23,800 --> 00:42:27,220
into the future, you take--
you calculate the difference

910
00:42:27,220 --> 00:42:31,300
between AEO projected CO2
emissions and actual CO2

911
00:42:31,300 --> 00:42:32,390
emissions.

912
00:42:32,390 --> 00:42:35,350
And then you do that
across all previous AEO

913
00:42:35,350 --> 00:42:37,812
editions for that
projection horizon, right?

914
00:42:37,812 --> 00:42:40,270
And then you repeat that for
different projection horizons.

915
00:42:40,270 --> 00:42:42,970
For 5 years, 10 years, 15 years.

916
00:42:42,970 --> 00:42:45,200
So for each projection
horizon there,

917
00:42:45,200 --> 00:42:47,890
then you've got two
set of differences

918
00:42:47,890 --> 00:42:49,660
between AEO and actual.

919
00:42:49,660 --> 00:42:54,040
And you can use that information
to form a distribution.

920
00:42:54,040 --> 00:42:56,110
And there's lots
of things to test.

921
00:42:56,110 --> 00:42:58,330
And you can assume
that you can fit it

922
00:42:58,330 --> 00:43:00,370
to a Gaussian distribution.

923
00:43:00,370 --> 00:43:02,500
And this particular
case, we assume

924
00:43:02,500 --> 00:43:08,150
that it was a
non-parametric distribution.

925
00:43:08,150 --> 00:43:09,940
And so what you
do is if you have

926
00:43:09,940 --> 00:43:12,800
a distribution for each
projection horizon,

927
00:43:12,800 --> 00:43:15,880
you can then use
that to fit a cone.

928
00:43:15,880 --> 00:43:18,860
And then you can apply that cone
to the current reference case.

929
00:43:18,860 --> 00:43:20,780
And that's what we've done here.

930
00:43:20,780 --> 00:43:23,990
So just to orient you, the
black line is a reference case.

931
00:43:23,990 --> 00:43:27,200
The two gray lines
are the most--

932
00:43:27,200 --> 00:43:31,610
the highest and lowest emissions
cases that we had in the AEO.

933
00:43:31,610 --> 00:43:33,800
And then you can see the cones.

934
00:43:33,800 --> 00:43:36,130
So the way to think
about the dark blue cone

935
00:43:36,130 --> 00:43:39,820
is that it captures 50% of
the historical projection

936
00:43:39,820 --> 00:43:43,880
errors in energy
related CO2 emissions.

937
00:43:43,880 --> 00:43:45,730
And then the lighter
blue cone captures

938
00:43:45,730 --> 00:43:49,192
95% of the historical
projection errors.

939
00:43:49,192 --> 00:43:50,650
There's a couple
of things I really

940
00:43:50,650 --> 00:43:52,280
like about this technique.

941
00:43:52,280 --> 00:43:54,770
One is that it's very
computationally efficient.

942
00:43:54,770 --> 00:43:57,550
We don't have to run
them hundreds of times

943
00:43:57,550 --> 00:44:00,560
because we have all of
this data lying around.

944
00:44:00,560 --> 00:44:02,260
So that's a really
big advantage.

945
00:44:02,260 --> 00:44:05,140
The other thing is that it
captures whatever bias there

946
00:44:05,140 --> 00:44:06,470
is in our projections.

947
00:44:06,470 --> 00:44:09,970
It's being captured
because we're

948
00:44:09,970 --> 00:44:14,630
comparing actual to projection.

949
00:44:14,630 --> 00:44:16,910
The thing that's the
weakness of this,

950
00:44:16,910 --> 00:44:20,080
though, is who's to say that
those historical projection

951
00:44:20,080 --> 00:44:22,070
errors apply to the future.

952
00:44:22,070 --> 00:44:23,780
We don't know-- we
don't know that.

953
00:44:23,780 --> 00:44:25,447
But I still think
that there's something

954
00:44:25,447 --> 00:44:30,120
useful to be learned
from this exercise.

955
00:44:30,120 --> 00:44:32,320
OK, final thing,
just very quickly,

956
00:44:32,320 --> 00:44:35,020
I want to talk about our
long term modeling plans.

957
00:44:35,020 --> 00:44:37,350
A couple of years ago,
we embarked on a plan

958
00:44:37,350 --> 00:44:41,130
to overhaul our
long term models.

959
00:44:41,130 --> 00:44:43,590
Before I get into that, I
wanted to explain, well,

960
00:44:43,590 --> 00:44:46,600
what are the goals for our
long term outlooks at EIA.

961
00:44:46,600 --> 00:44:48,930
I mean, we want to be
able to capture key market

962
00:44:48,930 --> 00:44:52,420
dynamics that drive energy
related decision making.

963
00:44:52,420 --> 00:44:55,870
We do want to provide that
policy neutral baseline.

964
00:44:55,870 --> 00:44:58,680
We do want to capture
uncertainty and capture

965
00:44:58,680 --> 00:45:01,240
the fullest range of
possible outcomes.

966
00:45:01,240 --> 00:45:03,750
And we want to be
flexible and nimble.

967
00:45:03,750 --> 00:45:06,180
We want to be able to
incorporate new model

968
00:45:06,180 --> 00:45:09,100
features easily and
produce timely analysis.

969
00:45:09,100 --> 00:45:11,340
And then, finally, we want
to make our modeling work

970
00:45:11,340 --> 00:45:13,580
transparent and accessible.

971
00:45:13,580 --> 00:45:16,440
The little snippet I
took here was actually

972
00:45:16,440 --> 00:45:19,460
from the Infrastructure
Investment and Jobs Act.

973
00:45:19,460 --> 00:45:21,720
This is actually
directed at EIA.

974
00:45:21,720 --> 00:45:25,440
And it's telling us
to strive to build

975
00:45:25,440 --> 00:45:30,160
a single, consistent, and
open source modeling platform.

976
00:45:30,160 --> 00:45:32,590
So we're on this
two-track approach.

977
00:45:32,590 --> 00:45:36,530
Track one is we need to
continue to produce the AEO.

978
00:45:36,530 --> 00:45:40,610
So we're updating the national
energy modeling system.

979
00:45:40,610 --> 00:45:44,120
One thing we did was we
made NEMS open source.

980
00:45:44,120 --> 00:45:46,910
So you can now go to GitHub,
you can clone the repo.

981
00:45:46,910 --> 00:45:49,700
It's available under
the Apache 2.0 license.

982
00:45:49,700 --> 00:45:54,790
So if you're feeling ambitious
and so forth, please have at it.

983
00:45:54,790 --> 00:45:55,880
Make use of the model.

984
00:45:55,880 --> 00:45:57,410
The data is also there as well.

985
00:45:57,410 --> 00:45:59,900
It takes some effort
to get it all set up,

986
00:45:59,900 --> 00:46:04,770
but we do-- but we are
making it available.

987
00:46:04,770 --> 00:46:08,890
The other thing, though, is that
we've overhauled the modules.

988
00:46:08,890 --> 00:46:12,343
So when we release
AEO 2025, it's

989
00:46:12,343 --> 00:46:14,010
going to be using a
version of NEMS that

990
00:46:14,010 --> 00:46:15,640
contains three new modules.

991
00:46:15,640 --> 00:46:18,240
There's going to be
a hydrogen market

992
00:46:18,240 --> 00:46:22,060
module that's going to represent
hydrogen production and pricing.

993
00:46:22,060 --> 00:46:24,960
There's a brand new
carbon management

994
00:46:24,960 --> 00:46:27,780
module that captures
